President Donald J. Trump has declared a major disaster in the Commonwealth of Kentucky due to severe storms, flooding, landslides, and mudslides that occurred from February 3 to February 29, 2020. This declaration allows for federal assistance to supplement recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be available to the Commonwealth, eligible local governments, and certain private nonprofit organizations for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The counties of Bell, Boyd, Butler, Clay, Harlan, Henderson, Hickman, Johnson, Knott, Knox, Lawrence, Leslie, Letcher, Lewis, Magoffin, McCracken, McCreary, Menifee, Metcalfe, Monroe, Morgan, Owsley, Perry, Pike, Powell, Union, and Whitley are eligible for this funding. Hazard mitigation measures for the entire Commonwealth are also eligible for federal funding. Allan Jarvis has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for Federal recovery operations in the affected areas. Additional designations may be made in the future if requested by the Commonwealth and based on further damage assessments. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.